<br>
And yes, it's Chlorine that breaks down ozone.  CFCs have to be broken down into Chlorine to cause damage to the ozone layer.  Ultraviolet radiation causes the breakdown of CFCs and, so far, CFCs have yet to be detected at the altitudes that would allow this breakdown.<br>
<br>
Besides, even if CFCs <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>were</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> found in measurable quantities at these altitudes, the total estimated (by the enviroweenies, that is) amount of chlorine released each year from CFCs is 10,500 tons.  This may sound like a lot, but consider that the Earth's oceans release 300 <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>million</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> tons of chlorine each year.  Active volcanoes spew 36 million tons of chlorine into the atmosphere each year.  So human &quot;chlorine&quot; output is maybe a few thousandths of one percent of naturally occurring chlorine.<br>
<br>
Bush is doing the right thing here.  The objective science shows not even the merest hint of danger of humans causing the kind of damage predicted by the environ<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>mental</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> crowd.  There's no need to hamstring a rebounding U.S. economy to satisfy a bunch of envious socialists.<br>
 <p>Sergian Singian`Smythe, Esq. of Erudin<br>
Gate Caller, Scholar, and et cetera and et cetera.<br>
