<br>
Being that as it may, would you be inclined to argue that air pollution is therefore an irrelevant thing that we needn't be concerned with, or is a bad thing which has a detrimental impact on our environment (in terms of acid rain and so forth), and our health (in terms of diminished lung capacity, increased incidence of asthma, etc)?<br>
<br>
And if you agree that air pollution is bad, at what point do you agree it's important to start doing something about it?  Only when it's absolutely free to fix the problem?  Only when your kid is suffering a respiratory illness because of it?<br>
<br>
I would make the arguments that:<br>
<br>
a) Even if air pollution has nothing to do with the depletion of the ozone layer, other problems associated with it are very well documented and we should be working very hard to reduce it.<br>
<br>
b) In the overall picture, the cost associated with running cleaner facilities is not only negligible, but would be passed on to consumers.  Before you walk out of a treaty you should do some hard polling.  I think if most people were asked if they personally would be willing to pay X dollars a year in energy costs to result in a net reduction of X tons of pollution being put into our atmosphere, most people would be in favor of the stricter standards.<br>
<br>
- Syll   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whistlerfv>Whistler FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 448<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/3/03 8:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=855.topic&index=45>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: US Refuses Ozone Protocol</span><hr size=1> Looks like Russia may do an about face on this issue.<br>
